===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|bold}}, {{m|enm|bald}}, {{m|enm|beald}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|bald}}, {{m|ang|beald||bold, brave, confident, strong, of good courage, presumptuous, impudent}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*balþaz||strong, bold}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bhel-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bhlē-||to bloat, swell, bubble}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|boud||bold, courageous, fearless}}, {{cog|gmh|balt||bold}} (whence {{cog|de|bald||soon}}), {{cog|sv|båld||bold, dauntless}}. Perhaps related to Albanian {{m|sq|ballë||forehead}} and Old Prussian {{m|prg|balo||forehead}}. For semantic development compare Italian {{m|it|affrontare||to face, to deal with}}, {{m|it|sfrontato||bold,daring}}, both from Latin {{m|la|frons||forehead}}.

